Therefore Ι think it should be held that the said sultriness is not infrequently the result osa tremulous and unequal movement of the air; for the air, when agitated by a motion of that kind, becomes very warm as the distinguished Descartes has remarked. For if any one blows vigorously against the back of the hand the breath is felt to be very cold; while, on the con- trary, il he blows it into the contracted and bent palm of the hand, it becomes not a little warm; the reason seems to be that when the aerial particles are thrown into a tremulous motion by being reflected hither and thither in the hollow hand, it happens that the nitro- aerial particles, by their striking against each other, are gentlydetached andthrown into the motion that is required for heat. But if a considerable tract of air is at any time agitated by such a motion, it will not only grow warm but will also be in a condition for entering upon a motion of the kind required lor the production of lightning.
